navigating diverse international funding regimes and authoritarian state institutions as entry points for understanding the pervasiveness of bureaucracy in contemporary science. He asks: What if we take the tools, sensibilities, and practices of bureaucracies seriously not only as objects of critique but as resources for re-thinking scientific practice? Extending a mode of anthropological research in which ethnography serves as source of theory as well as source of data, Science Interrupted thinks with, and not only against, bureaucracy. McLellan shows that ethnographic engagement with bureaucracy enables us to imagine more democratic and more collaborative modes of scientific practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgroforestryxResearchxDocumentationzChina, Southwest. 0aAgroforestryxResearchzChina, SouthwestxEvaluation. 0aBureaucracyzChina, Southwest. 0aResearch instituteszChina, SouthwestxEvaluation. 4aASIA. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  asouthwest China, bureaucracy, audit cultures, neoliberalization, scientific autonomy, anthropological research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773358?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773358/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles